ponsive design</li><li>Accessibility</li><li>Authentication</li><li>Privacy boundaries</li><li>Performance debugging</li><li>Data migration</li><li>Technical documentation</li></ul></article><article class="skill-card"><h3>Workplace</h3><ul class="tag-list" aria-label="Workplace skills"><li>Customer support</li><li>Data accuracy</li><li>Following procedures</li><li>Stock organisation</li><li>Order preparation</li><li>Teamwork</li><li>Timekeeping</li><li>Working under pressure</li><li>Clear communication</li><li>Problem solving</li></ul></article></div></div></section><section id="projects" class="section section-pad"><div class="container"><div class="section-heading narrow"><p class="eyebrow">Projects</p><h2>Flagship builds first. Production work after.</h2><p>I have ordered these by the strength of the engineering story they demonstrate. Each project states what is real, what was difficult and what still needs work.</p></div><div class="project-group-heading"><p class="eyebrow">Flagship builds</p><h3>The projects that show the most technical range and depth.</h3></div><div class="project-card-grid project-card-grid-flagship"><article class="project-card project-card-flagship project-card-game"><figure class="project-card-media"><img src="assets/the-world-forgot-us-card.svg" alt="The World Forgot Us project graphic showing a dark road network, cyan trace signal and warm carriage light."></figure><div class="project-card-body"><p class="eyebrow">Playable Godot campaign</p><h3>The World Forgot Us</h3><p>A top-down game set around a failed British civil-warning network. What began as a small vertical slice is now a playable four-area campaign with combat, saving, upgrades, environmental puzzles, optional records and three endings.</p><p>The technical core is persistent campaign state across authored and runtime-built maps. The same Trace Receiver drives exploration, enemy shield windows and story discovery, while region-aware lighting, generated normal maps and procedural audio give each area its own identity.</p><ul class="project-proof" aria-label="The World Forgot Us evidence"><li><strong>4</strong><span>connected campaign areas</span></li><li><strong>3</strong><span>ending routes</span></li><li><strong>10</strong><span>recoverable traces</span></li><li><strong>CI</strong><span>Godot smoke test and web export</span></li></ul><ul class="tag-list" aria-label="The World Forgot Us project skills"><li>Godot 4.7</li><li>GDScript</li><li>Campaign state</li><li>Real-time 2D lighting</li><li>Procedural audio</li><li>Web export</li><li>GitHub Actions</li></ul><div class="project-card-actions"><a class="button button-primary" href="https://jamiep-205.github.io/the-world-forgot-us/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Play in browser</a><a class="button button-ghost" href="https://github.com/JamieP-205/the-world-forgot-us" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub repo</a></div></div></article><article class="project-card project-card-flagship project-card-learning"><figure class="project-card-media"><img src="assets/french-for-life-card.svg" alt="French for Life project graphic showing its teach-before-test approach and technology stack."></figure><div class="project-card-body"><p class="eyebrow">Adaptive French platform</p><h3>French for Life</h3><p>An accuracy-first French-learning platform built around one strict rule: teach language before asking the learner to produce it. The public no-account demo runs in the browser and keeps 